<concept id="concept_1BCF5C425D7D4627AB1C66A085CF6E11"
            xml:lang="en-us">
    <title>Activating the <ph conref="../../Shared/Product_Name.xml#ProductNameTopic/Product_Abbr"/> Proxy</title>
    <conbody>
        <section>
            <p><ph conref="../../Shared/Product_Name.xml#ProductNameTopic/Product_Abbr"
                    /> provides a proxy which you can optionally activate to enable access to all <ph
                    conref="../../Shared/Product_Name.xml#ProductNameTopic/Product_Abbr"
                /> services and applications by the default HTTPS port (443). </p>
            <p>The proxy is deployed with <ph conref="../../Shared/Product_Name.xml#ProductNameTopic/Product_Abbr"
                    />. In order to activate it, however, you need to explicitly start its container, <codeph>oscm-proxy</codeph>, using its own Docker Compose file in the <codeph>/docker</codeph> directory:</p>
            <p>
                <codeblock>docker-compose -f docker-compose-proxy.yml up -d</codeblock>
            </p>
            <p>To stop the proxy again, execute:</p>
            <p>
                <codeblock>docker-compose -f docker-compose-proxy.yml down</codeblock>
            </p>
            <note>
                <p>The proxy is configured to handle the ports of <ph
                        conref="../../Shared/Product_Name.xml#ProductNameTopic/Product_Abbr"
                    />. However, you can also use it for additional services and applications by extending its configuration accordingly using NGINX syntax in the following file:</p>
                <p><codeph>/docker/config/oscm-proxy/data/proxy.conf</codeph></p>
                <p>Do not change any of the existing entries for <ph
                        conref="../../Shared/Product_Name.xml#ProductNameTopic/Product_Abbr"/>!</p>
            </note>
        </section>
    </conbody>
</concept>
